  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 620 mg
servings: 2
course: main course
---

In a medium #pot{}, combine @water{4%cups} and @Veggie Stock Concentrate{2}. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer.

Wash and dry all produce. Trim and thinly slice @Scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Heat a drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{1%tsp} in a large pan over medium heat. Add scallion whites; cook until softened, ~{1%minute}.

Add @Arborio Rice{3/4%cup} and 2 tsp @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tbsp}. (You'll use the rest of the Tuscan Heat Spice in the next step.) Stir until rice is translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add ½ cup stock; stir until liquid has mostly absorbed. Repeat with remaining stock—adding ½ cup at a time and stirring until liquid has mostly absorbed—until rice is al dente and mixture is creamy, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Once risotto has cooked ~{20%minutes}, trim and dice @Zucchini{1} into ½-inch pieces. Halve @Grape Tomatoes{4%oz}.

Heat 1 tsp @Basil Oil{5%tsp} in a second large pan over medium-high heat. (Save the rest of the basil oil for serving.)

Add zucchini and remaining Tuscan Heat Spice. Cook, stirring, until tender and lightly browned, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Add tomatoes and half the @Balsamic Vinegar{5%tsp} to pan with zucchini. Cook, stirring, until tomatoes have softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Turn off heat.

Once risotto is done, stir in @Butter{1%tbsp} and half the @Parmesan Cheese{1/4%cup}. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide risotto between bowls. Top with veggies, scallion greens, and remaining Parmesan. Drizzle with remaining basil oil to taste and serve.

> What’s not to love about risotto? It’s luxurious and comforting—one of those dishes that never fails to satisfy.

> Risotto has the reputation of being labor intensive, but this version couldn't be easier to whip up! It's topped with tangy balsamic-glazed zucchini and grape tomatoes, two perfect contrasts to risotto's creamy richness.